  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a clear consensus that **money laundering is against the law** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate, and it is universally recognized as a criminal activity. \n\nHere\u2019s why it\u2019s illegal:\n\n1. **Globally Criminalized**: Money laundering is prohibited under international treaties such as the **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**. Most countries have incorporated these standards into their national laws.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Nearly every country has enacted specific anti-money laundering (AML) legislation. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act (2001)** are key laws.\n   - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** provide a framework for member states.\n   - Other countries, such as the **UK**, **Canada**, and **Australia**, have robust AML laws as well.\n\n3. **Financial System Integrity**: Money laundering undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates organized crime, terrorism, corruption, and tax evasion, and distorts economies.\n\n4. **International Cooperation**: Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering and ensure countries implement effective measures. Non-compliance can result in sanctions or exclusion from international financial systems.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally illegal, and governments, international organizations, and financial institutions are committed to preventing and prosecuting it.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
